04342nam a22005895i 9780520941410DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209414107 a10.1525/97805209414102doi  a(DE-B1597)647900  a(OCoLC)801844691  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDF562b.M55 2006 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a949.50132231 aMillar, Fergus, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGreek Roman Empire :bPower and Belief under Theodosius II (408–450) /cFergus Millar; ed. by Fergus Millar. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (306 p.) :b5 b/w photographs, 7 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSather Classical Lectures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tAncient Sources: Texts, Editions, and Translations -- tI. ROMAN AND GREEK: STATE AND SUBJECT -- tII. SECURITY AND INSECURITY -- tIII. INTEGRATION AND DIVERSITY -- tIV. STATE AND CHURCH: CIVIL ADMINISTRATION, ECCLESIASTICAL HIERARCHY, AND SPIRITUAL POWER -- tV. STATE POWER AND MORAL DEFIANCE: NESTORIUS AND IRENAEUS -- tVI. PERSUASION, INFLUENCE, AND POWER -- tAppendix A. The Acta of the Fifth-Century Councils: A Brief Guide for Historians -- tAppendix B. Verbatim Reports of Proceedings from the Reign of Theodosius 11 -- tIllustrations -- tIndexes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first half of the fifth century, the Latin-speaking part of the Roman Empire suffered vast losses of territory to barbarian invaders. But in the Greek-speaking half of the Eastern Mediterranean, with its capital at Constantinople, there was a stable and successful system, using Latin as its official language, but communicating with its subjects in Greek. This book takes an inside look at how this system worked in the long reign of the pious Christian Emperor Theodosius II (408-50), and analyzes its largely successful defense of its frontiers, its internal coherence, and its relations with its subjects, with a flow of demands and suggestions traveling up the hierarchy to the Emperor, and a long series of laws, often set out in elaborately self-justificatory detail, addressed by the Emperor, through his officials, to the people. Above all, this book focuses on the Imperial mission to promote the unity of the Church, the State’s involvement in intensely-debated doctrinal questions, and the calling by the Emperor of two major Church Councils at Ephesus, in 431 and 449. Between the Law codes and the acts of the Church Councils, the material illustrating the working of government and the involvement of State and church, is incomparably richer, more detailed, and more vivid than for any previous period.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAncient. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aMillar, Fergus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMillar, Fergus, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025391940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094141040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520941410423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520941410/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles